3. He goes on in his deſires: Conſume them, O Lord, emphatically, conſume them in wrath that they may not be;
                      which at firſt ſight ſeems contrary to his firſt deſire, Slay them not: But it is not ſo,
Conſumed. for he ſpeaks not of their life, as if he would have them ſo conſumed, that they ſhould not remain alive; but he deſires only a conſumption of their power, royalty, command; &c. And ſo theſe words are a farther explication of his ſecond deſire, Bring them down: He would have them ſo brought down and conſumed in their ſtrength, dignity, command, wealth, riches, that made them proud, that they never be able any more to oppoſe God, hurt his people, trample upon Religion, and his Church; he would have them live.

